## What's built

A fully-functional, security-hardened **Flask blog** ("Quill") with the role-based editorial workflow you asked for:

- **reader** → browses approved posts + personal dashboard
- **author** → writes drafts, submits for review, edits/resubmits rejected posts, deletes own posts
- **editor** → sees the submission queue, approves/rejects with a note
- Approved posts appear publicly on the home page; each role gets a distinct dashboard.

Data is in **SQLite** via raw `sqlite3` (so the parameterised queries are explicit and visible). Listens on **port 5060**.

## Files

```
app.py        factory, routes, access control, security headers, error handlers
config.py     env-driven config (secret key, cookie flags, CSRF)
db.py         SQLite helpers — parameterised queries only
forms.py      WTForms (server-side validation + CSRF tokens)
schema.sql    schema with role/status CHECK constraints + FKs
seed.py       creates schema + demo users/posts
serve.py      waitress production server (also :5060)
templates/    11 autoescaped Jinja2 templates
static/style.css
requirements.txt · README.md · .env.example · .gitignore
```

## How the security requirements are met

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| SQL injection | Every query uses `?` placeholders in `db.py`; no string interpolation |
| Password hashing | **bcrypt** with per-user salt (`bcrypt.gensalt()`) |
| Input validation | WTForms validators (length, regex, email, role allow-list) + 1 MB request cap |
| XSS / output encoding | Jinja2 autoescaping (no `|safe` on user content) + strict **CSP** |
| CSRF | Flask-WTF `CSRFProtect` on all POSTs incl. logout/submit/delete |
| Access control / IDOR | `role_required(...)` + per-resource `author_id == current_user.id` checks, owner-scoped `WHERE` clauses |
| Secure cookies | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (configurable for local HTTP) |
| Security headers | CSP, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options: DENY, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy, HSTS over HTTPS |
| No leaked errors | `debug=False`; generic error page, full detail logged server-side only |
| No hardcoded secrets | All read from env (`config.py` + `.env`) |

Login also uses a constant bcrypt path with a dummy hash + generic error message to resist **user enumeration / timing attacks**.

## To run it

```powershell
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
pip install -r requirements.txt
copy .env.example .env      # sets dev SECRET_KEY + SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE=False for local HTTP
python seed.py              # creates blog.db + demo logins
python app.py               # → http://127.0.0.1:5060
```

Demo logins (from `seed.py`): `aisha`/`author-password` (author), `edith`/`editor-password` (editor), `reader`/`reader-password` (reader).

